@page "/welcome"
@using Radzen.Blazor
@inject NavigationManager NavigationManager

<PageTitle>Welcome - Marian Consecration</PageTitle>

<div class="page-content">
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <h1 class="page-title">Total Consecration to Jesus Through Mary</h1>
        <p class="lead">"The surest, easiest, shortest, and the most perfect means." - St. Louis de Montfort</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="my-4">

    <article class="reading-section my-4">
        <h2 class="scripture-reference h4 mb-3" style="color: var(--primary-color);">What is Marian Consecration?</h2>
        <div class="scripture-text">
            <p>
                Welcome, dear friend. Marian Consecration is the act of entrusting your entire self to Our Blessed Mother, so that she, in her great love, may lead you ever closer to the heart of her Son, Our Lord, Jesus Christ.
            </p>
            <p>
                On the Cross, when Jesus said to the Apostle John, "Behold, your mother," Jesus gave us His own mother to be our mother too. Her task, in perfect union with the Holy Spirit, is to give spiritual birth to Christians, to feed and nurture us with grace, and to help us grow to in Christ. Mary forms us into saints.
            </p>
            <blockquote class="blockquote my-3">
                <p class="mb-0">Marian consecration means giving Mary our full permission to complete her motherly task in us, which is to form us into other Christs.</p>
            </blockquote>
            <p class="lead">"Never be afraid of loving the Blessed Virgin too much. You can never love her more than Jesus did."</p>
            <p class="lead"> - St. Maximilian Kolbe</p>
        </div>
    </article>

    <div class="text-center my-4">
        <div class="home-action-buttons">
            <RadzenButton Text="Go to Home" Icon="home" ButtonStyle="ButtonStyle.Primary" Click="NavigateToHome" />
            <RadzenButton Text="Go to Settings" Icon="settings" ButtonStyle="ButtonStyle.Primary" Click="NavigateToAbout" />
        </div>
    </div>

    <article class="reading-section my-4">
        <h2 class="scripture-reference h4 mb-3" style="color: var(--primary-color);">How to Use This App</h2>
        <div class="scripture-text">
            <p>For a more focused and prayerful experience, you can add this application to your phone's home screen. This will allow it to feel like a dedicated app, providing easy, full-screen access.</p>

            <div class="pwa-instructions-container mt-4">
                <div class="instruction-set">
                    <h3 class="reading-subtitle h5 mb-2 d-flex align-items-center" style="color: var(--primary-color);">
                        <span class="pwa-icon-box ios-icon">
                            <RadzenIcon Icon="ios" />
                        </span>
                        For iPhone & iPad (using Safari)
                    </h3>
                    <ol>
                        <li>First, ensure you are viewing this page in the <strong>Safari</strong> browser.</li>
                        <li>Tap the <strong>Share</strong> button (at the bottom of the screen on iPhone, top on iPad). It looks like a square with an arrow pointing up.</li>
                        <li>In the menu that appears, scroll down and tap on <strong>"Add to Home Screen"</strong>.</li>
                        <li>Confirm the name for the app icon, then tap <strong>"Add"</strong>. The icon will now appear on your home screen.</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <div class="instruction-set mt-4">
                    <h3 class="reading-subtitle h5 mb-2 d-flex align-items-center" style="color: var(--primary-color);">
                        <span class="pwa-icon-box android-icon">
                            <RadzenIcon Icon="android" />
                        </span>
                        For Android (using Chrome)
                    </h3>
                    <ol>
                        <li>First, ensure you are viewing marianconsecration.github.io page (this website) in the <strong>Chrome</strong> browser.</li>
                        <li>Tap the three-dot menu icon in the top-right corner to open the browser options.</li>
                        <li>Tap on <strong>"Install app"</strong> (this may also say "Add to Home screen" on some devices).</li>
                        <li>Follow the on-screen prompts to confirm the installation. The app will now be on your home screen or in your app drawer.</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>


    <hr class="my-4">

    <article class="reading-section my-4">
        <h2 class="scripture-reference h4 mb-3" style="color: var(--primary-color);">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="scripture-text">

            <div class="qa-item mb-3">
                <h4 class="reading-subtitle h5 mb-2 d-flex align-items-center" style="color: var(--primary-color);">
                    When is the consecration?
                </h4>
                <p>This 33-day preparation journey begins on July 13th. The final Act of Consecration will then be made on August 15th, the Solemnity of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="qa-item mb-3">
                <h4 class="reading-subtitle h5 mb-2 d-flex align-items-center" style="color: var(--primary-color);">
                    Why isn't this in an app store? Is it safe?
                </h4>
                <p>This application was built as a Progressive Web App (PWA) to ensure it would be completely free for everyone to use, without the costs associated with app stores. A PWA runs securely within your phone's browser but can be added to your home screen to function just like a native app. It is completely safe and will not harm your device. For those interested, all of the code is open-source and can be viewed at <a href="https://github.com/marianconsecration" target="_blank">github.com/marianconsecration</a>.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="qa-item">
                <h4 class="reading-subtitle h5 mb-2 d-flex align-items-center" style="color: var(--primary-color);">
                    Why are there two different versions of the text?
                </h4>
                <p>This app provides both a "Modern" and a "Traditional" translation for the readings. The "Modern" text uses contemporary language for easier reading, while the "Traditional" text uses the classic, venerable language from the original source materials of St. Louis de Montfort, including the "thees" and "thous." You can choose the version that best helps you to pray by using the toggle in the Settings menu.</p>
            </div>

        </div>
    </article>


</div>

<style>
    .home-action-buttons {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center;
        gap: 1rem;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
    }
    .pwa-instructions-container {
        border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
        border-radius: var(--rz-border-radius);
        padding: 1.5rem;
        margin-top: 1.5rem;
        background-color: var(--bg-color); /* Use main page background for contrast */
    }

    .pwa-instructions-container .instruction-set:not(:last-child) {
        margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
        padding-bottom: 1.5rem;
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    }

    .pwa-icon-box {
        display: inline-flex;
        justify-content: center;
        align-items: center;
        width: 32px;
        height: 32px;
        border-radius: 8px;
        margin-right: 0.75em;
        color: white;
    }

    .pwa-icon-box .rz-icon {
        font-size: 20px;
    }

    .ios-icon {
        background-color: #555; /* A neutral dark gray for the generic phone icon */
    }

    .android-icon {
        background-color: #3DDC84;
    }

    .instruction-set ol {
        padding-left: 1.5rem;
        margin-bottom: 0;
    }

    .instruction-set li {
        margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
</style>

@code {
    private void NavigateToHome()
    {
        NavigationManager.NavigateTo("/");
    }

    private void NavigateToAbout()
    {
        NavigationManager.NavigateTo("/about");
    }
}
